%N A393374 Decimal expansion of the weight factor for Hermite-Gauss quadrature of degree 7 corresponding to abscissa A393370.
%C A393374 There are floor(k/2) positive zeros of the Hermite polynomial of degree k:
%C A393374    k | zeros                           | corresponding weights for Hermite-Gauss quadrature
%C A393374   ---+---------------------------------+----------------------------------------------------
%C A393374    2 | A010503                         | A019704
%C A393374    3 | 0, A115754                      | 10*A019717, A019708
%C A393374    4 | A393353, A393354                | A393355, A393356
%C A393374    5 | 0, A393357, A393358             | A245887, A393360, A393361
%C A393374    6 | A393362, A393363, A393364       | A393365, A393366, A393367
%C A393374    7 | 0, A393368, A393369, A393370    | A393371, A393372, A393373, this sequence
%H A393374 M. Abramowitz and I. A. Stegun, eds., <a href="http://www.convertit.com/Go/ConvertIt/Reference/AMS55.ASP">Handbook of Mathematical Functions</a>, National Bureau of Standards, Applied Math. Series 55, Tenth Printing, 1972 [alternative scanned copy]. Eq. 25.4.46 p. 890 and Table 25.10 p. 924.
%H A393374 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hermite-GaussQuadrature.html">Hermite-Gauss Quadrature</a>.
%F A393374 This constant divided by sqrt(Pi) is a root of 1234800*x^3 -335160*x^2 + 9303*x - 5 = 0 (see also A393904).
%e A393374 0.00097178124509951915414942425593895964444240121701...
%t A393374 RealDigits[Sqrt[Pi] * Root[1234800*x^3 - 335160*x^2 + 9303*x - 5, 1], 10, 100, -1][[1]] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 07 2026 *)
%o A393374 (PARI) sqrt(Pi)*polrootsreal(Pol([1234800, -335160, 9303, -5]))[1]
